Moselle: Cases of anthrax detected in several farms
---------------------------------------------------
25 cattle have already died from the disease. The authorities have started vaccinating several hundred animals.

Several cases of anthrax have been detected in recent days on 5 farms in Moselle [Alsace-Champagne-Ardenne-Lorraine region], where authorities have started vaccinating hundreds of animals, including sheep and cattle, as we learned Saturday [20 Aug 2016] from the prefecture.

In 3 farms, analyses since the beginning of the month on dead animals revealed that the animals were suffering from anthrax, said the prefecture of Moselle in a statement. These 1st cases were identified in the eastern department of pastures in Saint-Jean-de-Bassel and Fénétrange, which were added to the plots Berthelming, Gosselming and Langatte. "At 1st, the animals were subjected to antibiotic treatment. Now, vaccination is implemented in confirmed outbreaks as well as herds which are on adjacent land parcels contaminated," said the prefecture.

The rate of decline in mortality: Authorities have started vaccinating 3 flocks, including a herd of 225 animals -- the operation to be completed in the "course of the coming weekend" -- and a flock of sheep and another 20 cattle. "To date, 25 cattle have succumbed to the disease. However, the rate of mortality has slowed sharply in recent days," observes the Moselle prefecture. "Given the new cases, careful monitoring of state services is still required until all are vaccinated." The 5 affected farms are monitored by the Departmental Directorate of Protection of the Population of Moselle and the Regional Health Agency (ARS), which monitor the breeders, veterinarians and employees of the rendering company.

Anthrax is a disease caused by the bacterium _Bacillus anthracis_ which primarily affects animals but can also reach humans, in particular in contact with or through ingestion of infected animals. Most mammals are susceptible, but anthrax affects mainly ruminants. Treatment of infected animals is done with antibiotics, but vaccination is the most effective way to limit the spread of the disease.

